<rss version="2.0" xmlns:atom="http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom"><channel><title><![CDATA[WSJ - EN-US - opinion]]></title><link/> https://www.wsj.com/news/opinion <atom:link href="https://rsshub.app/wsj/en-us/opinion" rel="self" type="application/rss+xml"></atom:link><description><![CDATA[WSJ - EN-US - opinion - Made with love by RSSHub(https://github.com/DIYgod/RSSHub)]]></description><generator> RS集线器</generator><webmaster>i@diygod.me (DIYgod)</webmaster><language> zh-cn</language><lastbuilddate> 2023 年 8 月 16 日星期三 01:37:46 GMT</lastbuilddate><ttl> 120 </ttl><item><title><![CDATA[Indictment Four: Trump as Racketeer]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>指控 RICO 阴谋使佐治亚州 2020 年选举案件的可信度降低。 <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB11442211204531153375304590152133790031758"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB11442211204531153375304590152133790031758"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/editorial-board" itemprop="url" rel="author">编委会</a></span>撰文</div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 15 日下午 6:47 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/donald-trump-georgia-indictment-fani-willis-rico-2020-election-brad-raffensperger-cd592c20"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-836286?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> 8 月 15 日，富尔顿县地方检察官法尼·威利斯 (Fani Willis) 在亚特兰大讨论了对前总统唐纳德·特朗普的起诉书。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：迈克尔·布莱克希尔/祖玛出版社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>对前总统<a href="https://www.wsj.com/topics/person/donald-trump">唐纳德·特朗普</a>的第四份起诉书读起来就像是一次练习，将所有事情都抛给陪审团，看看哪些内容可能会成立。佐治亚州富尔顿县民主党地区检察官法尼·威利斯 (Fani Willis) 整理了一份长达 98 页的指控表，其中包含 41 项罪名和 19 名被告，但关于特朗普的新证据却很少。</p><p>最大的新闻是地方检察官使用了该州的《诈骗影响和腐败组织法案》（RICO）。它将特朗普先生扭转 2020 年选举的企图视为黑手党行动，而不是那些在佐治亚州或其他任何地方都没有控制选举机制的笨手笨脚的人。被指控的行为很糟糕，但将其夸大为 RICO 阴谋只会让案件变得不那么可信，而不是更可信。</p><div class="media-object scope-web,mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p>我们应该补充一点，当时任美国检察官鲁迪·朱利安尼 (Rudy Giuliani) 在 20 世纪 80 年代使用 RICO 来对付华尔街时，这些专栏批评了 RICO 的用途，而不是用于打击有组织犯罪。现在，讽刺的是，《纽约太阳报》注意到朱利安尼先生被指控违反《RICO》。现在它的使用并不比当时更好。</p><p>与特别检察官杰克·史密斯的联邦起诉书不同，佐治亚州的文件并未涉及特朗普先生根据第一修正案的言论自由。特朗普先生的每一条不成熟的推文都被视为另一项 RICO 行为：“唐纳德·约翰·特朗普 (Donald JOHN TRUMP) 的推特账户 @RealDonaldTrump 发布了推文，‘副总统有权拒绝以欺诈手段选出的选民。’”这是一种公然助长阴谋的行为。”威利斯女士正在将天才的计算带入绝望。</p><p>特朗普还被指控煽动一名公职人员违反他的誓言，因为他曾敦促国务卿布拉德·拉芬斯佩格找到足够的选票来推翻佐治亚州的选举结果。通话中最糟糕的部分是特朗普警告拉芬斯佩格先生正在冒“很大的风险”，因为未能报告欺诈行为“这是刑事犯罪”。</p><p>但威利斯女士能否证明特朗普先生的行为是犯罪行为，而不是妄想呢？ “我没有失去这个州，布拉德，”特朗普先生说。 “人们一直说这是有史以来最高的投票。没有办法。”他感到困惑的是，其他共和党人没有失败，而他却失败了。 “例如，他们在佐治亚州有人赢了，而我远远领先于他们，”特朗普在 2020 年 12 月的一次电话会议上对一名州调查员说道。 “他们称之为大衣下摆，对吧，我们把它们拉过去，他们说，‘我不可能以 15 分的优势击败你。’”</p><p>显而易见的答案是，郊区共和党人中决定性的一部分不希望特朗普先生再执政四年。威斯康星州的选区<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-best-summary-of-the-2020-election-biden-wisconsin-trump-lawsuit-voting-rights-fraud-absentee-dropboxes-ballot-curing-big-lie-11642966744?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">手工重新计票</a>发现，拜登总统的选票中有 10.5% 的选票投给了国会的共和党。 <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-wisconsin-gops-latest-meltdown-dean-knudson-election-commission-donald-trump-11653689063?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">特朗普以 63,547 票的优势落后于</a>威斯康星州的五位共和党国会议员，而拜登在这些竞选中以 64,880 票领先于民主党。在密尔沃基，特朗普的得票率实际上从 2016 年的 18.4% 提高到了 19.6%。</p><p>但特朗普先生的耳朵里却有蛇在低语着相反的声音。前副总统<a href="https://www.wsj.com/topics/person/mike-pence">迈克·彭斯</a>上周表示：“总统在任何时候都没有告诉我他知道自己输了。”</p><p>特朗普的律师将首先寻求将案件从佐治亚州移交给联邦法院，他们的观点是有道理的。许多涉嫌 RICO 的行为都与宾夕法尼亚州、亚利桑那州和其他有争议州的事件有关。</p><p>与史密斯起诉书一样，特朗普也有合理的理由声称，对其作为总统的职责所采取的行动享有“绝对豁免权”，包括试图揭露选民欺诈行为。请参阅最高法院 1982 年对<em>尼克松诉菲茨杰拉德一</em>案的裁决。记者团无视这种辩护，但随后他们往往会因法律上的意外而措手不及。</p><p>起诉书中最具破坏性的部分是指控律师西德尼·鲍威尔聘请富尔顿县承包商前往咖啡县的罪名，该团队显然在那里会见了富有同情心的当时的选举主管。起诉书称，其意图包括“篡改”选举设备和“删除选民数据”。投票机的物理安全至关重要，但这些罪名不包括特朗普先生，可以作为计算机犯罪的单独起诉书提出。</p><h4> ***</h4><p>佐治亚州的起诉书不太可能改变公众舆论，部分原因是其范围和时机。威利斯女士花了两年半的时间进行调查。现在，她希望在 6 个月内（​​即 2024 年初选中期）进行审判。在看到检察官，尤其是纽约检察官阿尔文·布拉格（Alvin Bragg）扩大法律范围来围堵特朗普后，许多共和党人聚集到了他一边。更多的起诉并没有改变这一点。</p><p>特朗普先生在 2020 年大选后的恶劣行为是无可辩驳的，共和党人的尝试将是一个错误。但大多数共和党人在审视这些起诉书以及希拉里·克林顿和亨特·拜登的通行证时，都会看到党派起诉和双重标准。四份起诉书之后，起诉特朗普，而不是把判断留给选民和历史，对这个国家来说似乎仍然是一个坏主意。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=5DE7BC77-6402-4B80-A5E9-9E8AC3644D45&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fdonald-trump-georgia-indictment-fani-willis-rico-2020-election-brad-raffensperger-cd592c20&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">杂志社论报道：司法部加速法律攻势。图片：Zuma Press/AFP/Getty Images 合成：Mark Kelly<span class="imageCredit">华尔街日报互动版</span></p></div></div></section></div></main></div>]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 15 Aug 2023 22:47:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/donald-trump-georgia-indictment-fani-willis-rico-2020-election-brad-raffensperger-cd592c20</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/donald-trump-georgia-indictment-fani-willis-rico-2020-election-brad-raffensperger-cd592c20<author><![CDATA[The Editorial Board]]></author><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>犯罪/法律诉讼</category><category>欺诈罪</category><category>犯罪企业</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>选举</category><category>国家/总统选举</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论/意见</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>唐纳德·特朗普</category><category>法尼·威利斯</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>犯罪</category><category>合法举动</category><category>欺诈罪</category><category>犯罪企业</category><category>政治</category><category>国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>选举</category><category>国家的</category><category>总统选举</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论</category><category>意见</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Brian Kemp’s Election Reality Test]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>事件证明共和党佐治亚州州长抵制唐纳德·特朗普窃取选举的说法是正确的。 <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB11442211204531153375304590152644056936592"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB11442211204531153375304590152644056936592"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/editorial-board" itemprop="url" rel="author">编委会</a></span>撰文</div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 15 日下午 6:44 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/brian-kemp-georgia-2020-election-donald-trump-indictment-d7049de4"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-836287?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">佐治亚州州长布莱恩·坎普</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Hyosub Shin/亚特兰大宪法报/美联社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>民主党人和媒体继续兜售<a href="https://www.wsj.com/topics/person/donald-trump">唐纳德·特朗普</a>推翻 2020 年大选的努力的一个神话是，特朗普差一点就成功了。但正如佐治亚州最新的起诉书所示，它从未真正获得过机会。</p><div class="media-object scope-web,mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p>所谓的特朗普阴谋者疯狂而笨手笨脚的努力在各个方面都受到共和党官员的阻挠。前副总统<a href="https://www.wsj.com/topics/person/mike-pence">迈克·彭斯</a>拒绝停止计票。让各州在<a href="https://www.wsj.com/topics/person/joe-biden">乔·拜登</a>赢得的州选择有利于唐纳德·特朗普的替代选举人名单的计划在每个州都惨遭失败。</p><p>在佐治亚州，坚定支持者包括州长布莱恩·坎普(Brian Kemp)和国务卿布拉德·拉芬斯佩格(Brad Raffensperger)，他们私下里受到特朗普的支持，公开也受到特朗普的谴责。</p><p>周二，新起诉书公布后，坎普先生并没有幸灾乐祸，但他确实触及了共和党政治问题的核心：</p><p> “佐治亚州 2020 年选举没有被窃取。近三年来，任何拥有欺诈证据的人都未能在宣誓后出庭并在法庭上证明任何事情。我们在佐治亚州的选举是安全、方便和公平的，并且只要我担任州长，选举就会继续进行。 2024 年我们国家的未来岌岌可危，这必须成为我们的重点。”</p><p>坎普先生会受到特朗普合唱团的谩骂，但他是对的，这句话值得赞扬。与此同时，周二，特朗普承诺他很快就会收到一份“无可辩驳的报告”，证明他在 2020 年获胜。共和党选民可能认为针对特朗普的起诉带有党派之争。但如果他们想在 2024 年再次失败，他们就会跳入特朗普先生的 2020 年兔子洞，而不是面对坎普先生的现实。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=5DE7BC77-6402-4B80-A5E9-9E8AC3644D45&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fbrian-kemp-georgia-2020-election-donald-trump-indictment-d7049de4&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">杂志社论报道：司法部加速法律攻势。图片：Zuma Press/AFP/Getty Images 合成：Mark Kelly<span class="imageCredit">华尔街日报互动版</span></p></div></div></section></div></main></div>]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 15 Aug 2023 22:44:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/brian-kemp-georgia-2020-election-donald-trump-indictment-d7049de4</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/brian-kemp-georgia-2020-election-donald-trump-indictment-d7049de4<author><![CDATA[The Editorial Board]]></author><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>犯罪/法律诉讼</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>地区政治</category><category>入室盗窃/盗窃</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论/意见</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>共和党</category><category>唐纳德·特朗普</category><category>布赖恩·肯普</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>犯罪</category><category>合法举动</category><category>政治</category><category>国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>地区政治</category><category>盗窃</category><category>盗窃</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论</category><category>意见</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[China’s Young, Restless—and Jobless]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>随着情况变得更糟，北京不会公布青年失业数据。 <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB12263517457060764701004590152403683414256"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB12263517457060764701004590152403683414256"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/editorial-board" itemprop="url" rel="author">编委会</a></span>撰文</div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 15 日下午 6:40 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-youth-unemployment-data-transparency-beijing-xi-jinping-e53dab3d"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-836288?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> 6月30日，人们在北京一家商场参加招聘会。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：托马斯·彼得/路透社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>最新经济数据显示中国经济持续疲软，美国股市周二走高。令投资者不安的另一个原因是中国政府暂停公布青年失业数据，而这一数据正值共产党发起限制透明度的运动。</p><p>随着中国最大的开发商之一碧桂园濒临违约，中国房地产泡沫的破灭引发了投资者对金融危机蔓延的担忧。周一有媒体报道称，中国最大的金融公司之一中植企业集团旗下的信托公司拖欠客户款项。</p><p>但未知的风险通常比已知的风险更令人担忧。近几个月来，北京一直在加强对向公众分享经济信息的限制。新修订的反间谍法将共享敏感经济信息定为犯罪。对于“敏感”，请阅读否定。毫不奇怪，中国经济分析师变得守口如瓶。</p><p>证券监管机构已要求国内律师事务所审查投资者披露信息中有关中国的负面语言。公司不应讨论经济中的“不利变化”，而应将其描述为“不断发展”。如果奥威尔式的双关语没有预示着政府范围内限制获取重要经济信息的运动，那么它就是滑稽的共产主义。</p><p>这也是如何解读北京在进行政府所谓的“进一步优化”和统计数据研究的同时停止公布青年失业率的决定。由于习近平主席实施零新冠政策以及对科技行业和其他威胁共产党政治控制的行业的监管打压，中国官方公布的青年失业率自 2019 年以来翻了一番，达到 21.3%。</p><p>过去两年，中国主要科技公司市值缩水超过1万亿美元，并解雇了数十万名员工。多年来，政府一直在推动房地产和电动汽车等受青睐的行业发展，但这些行业现在正在萎缩。过去几年，数百家电动汽车初创公司破产。</p><p>许多受过高等教育的中国年轻人在自己选择的领域找不到工作，因此退出了劳动力市场，他们将其描述为“平躺着”。北京大学的一位经济学家估计，如果算上数百万停止找工作的工人，今年春天青年失业率将达到46.5%。</p><p>政府告诉大学毕业生接受低薪蓝领工作。 “越有野心，就越要脚踏实地，”共产党的《人民日报》上个月表示。对失业数据进行审查的目的是为了在越来越多的受过教育、幻想破灭、焦躁不安的年轻人中维护社会稳定，这些年轻人可能成为政治动荡的根源。</p><p>但缺乏透明度的代价是人们对中国金融市场的信心下降。尤其是在经济疲软时期，缺乏透明度可能会加剧金融恐慌。政府正试图吸引更多外国投资，但这却给投资者带来了另一个逃跑的理由。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=68BC093E-DA21-443E-8012-3A7C9C26F1F9&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fchina-youth-unemployment-data-transparency-beijing-xi-jinping-e53dab3d&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">杂志社论报道：习近平在莫斯科会见普京以巩固关系。图片：Shutterstock/讲义来自路透社 综合：Mark Kelly<span class="imageCredit">华尔街日报互动版</span></p></div></div></section></div></main></div>]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 15 Aug 2023 22:40:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-youth-unemployment-data-transparency-beijing-xi-jinping-e53dab3d</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-youth-unemployment-data-transparency-beijing-xi-jinping-e53dab3d<author><![CDATA[The Editorial Board]]></author><category>法规/政府政策</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>经济表现/指标</category><category>就业/失业数据</category><category>经济新闻</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论/意见</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>习近平</category><category>规定</category><category>政府政策</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>经济表现</category><category>指标</category><category>就业</category><category>失业数字</category><category>经济新闻</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>政治</category><category>国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论</category><category>意见</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[The Military Recruiting Crisis and Gen Z]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>学生们讨论入伍和在武装部队服役。 <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB12263517457060764701004590152290492221802"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB12263517457060764701004590152290492221802"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 15 日下午 6:21 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-military-recruiting-crisis-and-gen-z-obesity-patriotism-college-students-national-security-fitness-mental-health-ffb7482"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-835983?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> 7 月 5 日，马里兰州米德堡新兵入伍。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：安娜·钱梅梅克/盖蒂图片社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p><strong></strong><em>编者注：在这篇<a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/types/future-view?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">《未来展望》</a>中，学生们讨论征兵问题。接下来我们要问：“在平权行动决定之后，一些学院和大学已经开始停止对校友子女的特殊考虑。大学是否应该在申请中考虑传统招生？禁令会削弱社区意识和校友参与感吗？还是这种做法对其他申请人不公平？”学生请于8月29日之前<a href="https://futureview.wsj.com/" target="_blank" class="icon none">点击此处</a>提交250字以内的意见。最佳答案将于当晚公布。</em></p><p><em></em></p><p><strong>一种新型士兵</strong></p><p>年轻人身体和心理健康状况的下降导致许多人没有服兵役的资格，这令人担忧，但这可能不是一个严重的国家安全问题。这是因为我们消灭恐怖分子和挫败袭击的方法现在更多地依赖于技术而不是人力。</p><p> 2011 年击毙奥萨马·本·拉登需要两架直升机，其中载有两打海豹突击队队员。 2020 年，美国用无人机和遥控器杀死了伊朗第二号人物卡西姆·苏莱马尼 (Qasem Soleimani)。技术在军事中的作用正在不断发展，很难想象此类行动需要美军在接下来的八年内部署到地面。</p><p>更令人担忧的是，与中国和俄罗斯相比，美国缺乏技术人才。我们最应该关心的是精通数学、科学和网络安全的学生的百分比。</p><p>解决这个问题的最佳方法之一是在后备军官训练队项目上投入更多资金，这些项目培养技术人才和军事级别的纪律。我希望我在上大学时就知道这一点，并且应该付出更多的努力来宣传它。美国的军费开支超过了接下来 10 个开支最高的国家的总和，我们没有理由不认真努力扩大此类有效的项目。</p><p> <em>—Peter Iossa，宾夕法尼亚州立大学，物理学</em></p><p><em></em></p><p><strong>失去经济激励</strong></p><p>军队在工人阶级的经济流动性方面发挥着重要作用。这通常会推动招聘。我的一些同龄人之所以能够上大学，只是因为《退伍军人权利法案》和其他相关福利，这些福利使他们免受不断加剧的大学债务危机的影响。公众对大学债务减免和其他类似措施的支持损害了这种入伍激励。随着社会安全网的扩大，军队将不得不寻找其他方式来吸引潜在的新兵。</p><p>入伍决定也受到公众情绪的影响，尤其是 Z 世代——招聘人员的目标人群。我无数次听说入伍是一个陷阱：与拥有一定大学学位的同龄人相比，服役的人的收入可能落后于曲线。随着老式美国爱国主义的丧失和微薄的经济激励，Z 世代对军队不感兴趣也就不足为奇了。</p><p> <em>—Trey Livian，加州大学伯克利分校，经济学</em></p><p><em></em></p><p><strong>Z世代失明问题</strong></p><p>反美情绪和身体健康标准下降的叠加导致 18 至 24 岁的年轻人中 80% 被认为不适合服役，这加剧了入伍与退休的比率。</p><p>对于 Z 世代来说，为国家服务的理念意味着作为一名积极分子，带头开展运动，并向任何敢于提出不同意见的人发出口头警告。这一代人被玫瑰色眼镜蒙蔽了双眼，拒绝接受现实，直到为时已晚。我们必须把头脑从智能手机中抽离出来，审视诸如消除政治极化和灌输民族自豪感等必要的变革。</p><p>如果需要的话，我会自愿去保护我的国家。美国人认为自由是理所当然的，并认为自由将永远受到保护。但如果我们不教导这一代人他们的自由可以被剥夺，那么这个国家就会处于危险之中。</p><p> <em>—Evelyne Holland，东南大学传播与大众媒体</em></p><p><em></em></p><p><strong>一切政治化</strong></p><p>根据里根国防调查，62%的美国人认为军事领导层变得过度政治化，降低了他们对武装部队的信心，近60%的人表示这是由于总统缺乏能力造成的。为了解决这个问题，军方必须放弃其政治姿态并确认其核心价值观：保护美国的自由，而不是设计它们。</p><p>由于这种政治化而对美国机构失去信心应该令人深感担忧。美国五分之四的年轻人因超重、吸毒或不符合军队的其他身体和精神标准而不适合服役。但更令人担忧的是，健康的人不愿意加入。</p><p>如果美国灌输纪律、卓越并提供大量不受社会政治影响的机会，年轻人将再次开始加入。军队不应受到政治审查。美国人最好记住海军陆战队的座右铭：对彼此、对我们的国家以及未来的战斗“永远忠诚”。</p><p> <em>—Kelley Foley，佛罗里达大西洋大学，金融专业</em></p><p><em></em></p><p><a href="https://futureview.wsj.com/" target="_blank" class="icon none">单击此处</a>提交对下周未来展望的回复。</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 15 Aug 2023 22:21:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-military-recruiting-crisis-and-gen-z-obesity-patriotism-college-students-national-security-fitness-mental-health-ffb7482</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-military-recruiting-crisis-and-gen-z-obesity-patriotism-college-students-national-security-fitness-mental-health-ffb7482<category>大学</category><category>学生</category><category>教育</category><category>军队</category><category>国家安全</category><category>战争</category><category>防御</category><category>爱国主义</category><category>服务</category><category>肥胖</category><category>健康</category><category>平权行动</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>国家/公共安全</category><category>世代群组</category><category>社会/社区</category><category>歧视</category><category>武装部队</category><category>教育</category><category>人权/公民自由</category><category>社会问题</category><category>大学学院</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论/意见</category><category>社论</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>平权行动</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>国家的</category><category>公安</category><category>代际群体</category><category>社会</category><category>社区</category><category>歧视</category><category>武装部队</category><category>人权</category><category>公民权利</category><category>社会问题</category><category>大学</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论</category><category>意见</category><category>社论</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Rent Control Is Constitutionally Vulnerable]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>纽约 2019 年的法律过于繁琐，以至于最高法院可能多年来首次重新审理该问题。 <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB12165777042486313942804590144793489416562"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB12165777042486313942804590144793489416562"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"><span class="author" itemprop="name">亚历山大·塔勒尔</span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 15 日下午 6:10 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/rent-control-is-constitutionally-vulnerable-new-york-law-housing-stabilization-economy-supreme-court-5a44edfa"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-835309?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> 2022 年 4 月 28 日，纽约的一场租户抗议。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：迈克尔·M·圣地亚哥/盖蒂图片社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>租金管制是否符合宪法？看看判例法，答案似乎是肯定的。正如瑟古德·马歇尔法官在<em>《洛雷托诉提词器曼哈顿有线电视公司》</em> （1982 年）一案中所说，最高法院“一贯确认各州拥有广泛的权力来监管一般的住房条件，特别是房东与房客的关系”。</p><p>但法官们也承认，规则必须是“适当的”，并且“如果监管过度，将被视为必须支付赔偿的征收行为”，正如法官奥利弗·温德尔·霍姆斯在<em>宾夕法尼亚煤炭公司</em>所写的那样。<em>诉马洪</em>(1922)。纽约州 2019 年住房稳定和租户保护法案修订了纽约市的租金稳定制度，使其面临宪法挑战的时机成熟。</p><p>纽约的租金稳定法最初于 1969 年颁布，迫使某些城市的房东以远低于市场的租金水平提供事实上的永久租赁。然而，在 2019 年之前，房东可以在某些条件下退出租金稳定计划。 2019 年法律取消了这些例外情况。</p><p>一群房东提起诉讼并败诉。今年 2 月，美国第二巡回上诉法院确认了初审法院的裁决，即租金稳定，即使是 2019 年的版本，也不是政府征收的，这需要根据第五修正案进行赔偿。房东们已请求法官审理上诉。</p><p>继 1969 年法律之后，1974 年又颁布了《紧急租户保护法》，该法案允许州政府在宣布住房“紧急状态”时恢复租金稳定。此后，该州定期发布这一声明，防止租金稳定政策到期，尽管 1993 年的修正案允许房东在公寓空置或租户收入和月租金均超过一定阈值时逃避租金稳定政策。 2019 年的法律有效地取消了放松管制和“日落条款”（即在没有“紧急”声明的情况下租金稳定到期的日期），从而确保租金稳定将永远适用于每套涵盖的公寓。</p><p>在对之前的法律多次提出法律挑战但未成功后，<em>社区住房改善计划诉纽约市对</em>2019 年版本提出了挑战。第二巡回法院适用了<em>宾夕法尼亚中央交通诉纽约市案</em>（1978 年），这是一项最高法院的裁决，涉及对该市地标保护法的质疑。<em>宾夕法尼亚中央大学</em>鼓励法院在审查征用索赔时进行“本质上是临时的事实调查”，考虑几个因素，包括法定计划对土地所有者的经济影响、该计划干扰土地所有者的投资支持预期的程度，以及政府行为的性质。第二巡回法院认为，租金稳定并不一定会对房东造成经济损害，立法机关的判决应该得到广泛尊重。</p><p>但这种公式化的决定忽视了租金监管的经济危害——而其他政策也隐含地承认了这一点。纽约州为住宅建筑开发商提供减税优惠，允许部分新单元的租金稳定。如果政府对自愿提供低于市场价格的出租公寓的业主进行补偿，它怎么能拒绝补偿那些它强迫这样做的人呢？租金稳定带来的巨额征用破坏了其增加经济适用住房供应量的既定目标。拥有租金稳定公寓的业主已经开始“仓储”这些公寓——让它们空置，以防止商业上受到破坏的租户永久占用。</p><p>上诉人没有敦促第二<em>巡回</em>法院采用安东宁·斯卡利亚法官制定的更针对具体情况的标准，而不是宾夕法尼亚中央大学。斯卡利亚在《佩内尔诉圣何塞案<em>》（Pennell v. San Jose</em> ，1988）中写道，如果旨在治愈社会弊病的价格监管阻碍了其所有者既没有造成也没有促成这种弊病的财产——在这种情况下，市场租金使租户——该规定相当于征用。只有桑德拉·戴·奥康纳法官赞同斯卡利亚在<em>彭内尔案</em>中的观点。</p><p>第二巡回法院的意见在冗长的脚注中引用了斯卡利亚提出的标准，其结论如下：“我们拒绝采用最高法院从未采用过的测试。”这是正确的做法；上诉法院有义务遵循最高法院的判例。上诉请愿书是法官重新审视的一个机会。</p><p>斯卡利亚的标准反对这样一种观念，即立法机关监管房东与房客关系的“广泛权力”使此类监管免受严格的宪法审查。他写道：“政府通过地主与租客关系采取行动的事实并没有神奇地将必须得到全体公众支持的一般公共福利转变为纯粹的‘经济监管’，而这可能会给特定个人带来不成比例的负担。”</p><p>斯卡利亚进一步指出，“美国政府解决那些无法以合理价格购买私人出售的必需品的人的问题（这是整个社会造成的问题）的传统方式是向这些人分配从公共机构筹集的资金。”通过税收，无论是现金（福利支付）还是商品（公共住房、公共补贴住房和食品券）。”</p><p>纽约的租金稳定计划本质上是一项公益计划。这可能是一件值得的事。但它利用私有财产来实现公共目的。因此，宪法要求其成本由公众承担，无论是通过税收优惠还是适用于所有受影响建筑物的某种同等补偿。</p><p><em>塔勒尔先生是一名私人执业律师。他曾担任美国第二巡回上诉法院法官 Jon O. Newman 和美国纽约南区地方法院法官 Sidney H. Stein 的法律助理。</em> </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=A385DE1C-F70D-402A-98B9-3B5374C21F0F&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Frent-control-is-constitutionally-vulnerable-new-york-law-housing-stabilization-economy-supreme-court-5a44edfa&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">期刊编辑报告：金·斯特拉塞尔 (Kim Strassel)、凯特·巴舍尔德·奥德尔 (Kate Bachelder Odell)、阿莉西亚·芬利 (Alysia Finley) 和丹·亨宁格 (Dan Henninger) 分享了本周最好和最差的内容。图片来源：Scott Morgan/Reuters<span class="imageCredit">华尔街日报互动版</span></p></div></div></section></div></main></div>]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 15 Aug 2023 22:10:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/rent-control-is-constitutionally-vulnerable-new-york-law-housing-stabilization-economy-supreme-court-5a44edfa</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/rent-control-is-constitutionally-vulnerable-new-york-law-housing-stabilization-economy-supreme-court-5a44edfa<category>纽约</category><category>租</category><category>住房</category><category>宪法</category><category>法律</category><category>房东</category><category>租金管制</category><category>规定</category><category>最高法院</category><category>租金稳定</category><category>房地产/建筑</category><category>房地产</category><category>法规/政府政策</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>经济适用房/社会住房</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>社会/社区</category><category>犯罪/法律诉讼</category><category>住房问题</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>社会问题</category><category>福利/社会服务</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论/意见</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>观点</category><category>政府政策</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>负担得起的</category><category>公益住房</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>社会</category><category>社区</category><category>犯罪</category><category>合法举动</category><category>住房问题</category><category>政治</category><category>国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>社会问题</category><category>福利</category><category>社会服务</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论</category><category>意见</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>观点</category><category>房地产</category><category>建造</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[A Prosperous Year for the Inflation Reduction Act]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>对电动汽车的需求刺激了中西部和南部新工厂的“电池带”。 <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB12263517457060764701004590150442418557252"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB12263517457060764701004590150442418557252"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">珍<span class="author" itemprop="name">妮特·耶伦</span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 15 日下午 6:07 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/a-prosperous-year-for-the-inflation-reduction-act-climate-change-net-zero-heat-global-warming-c2c07f0f"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-835466?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> 7 月 17 日，凤凰城的一辆自动驾驶汽车。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：ROB SCHUMACHER/今日美国网络/来自路透社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>当我在 20 世纪 90 年代末发表第一次重要气候演讲时，许多人仍然认为气候变化的影响是抽象和遥远的。不再。今天，没有人可以忽视气候变化对我们的星球和我们的生活方式造成的不稳定影响的越来越多的证据。</p><p>今年夏天，美国人亲眼目睹了这一点。从菲尼克斯到迈阿密，过去几个月天气异常炎热。该国大部分地区被国外山火的烟雾笼罩，而其他地区则遭受洪水和干旱。</p><p>这些现象造成了严重的经济代价，包括生产能力的损失以及对宏观经济稳定的潜在长期威胁。</p><p>一年前，拜登总统将《减少通货膨胀法案》签署为法律。这是美国历史上最大胆的气候行动，推动我们到 2050 年实现净零经济。随着时间的推移，《通货膨胀削减法案》将降低清洁能源技术的成本，从而促进清洁能源技术的采用并减少全球排放。</p><p>该法律还旨在推进另外两个目标：经济机会和复原力。它已经在这两个方面取得了成效。</p><p>建设清洁能源经济是我们一生中最大的经济转型之一。全球每年对清洁能源的投资已超过1万亿美元。长期以来，美国缺乏协调一致的战略来引领低碳技术和未来其他产业的发展。通过《降低通胀法案》，我们正在实现我所说的“现代供给侧”经济学：一个为拜登经济学注入活力的政策框架。它包括政府投资以动员私人资本、刺激经济增长并帮助美国实现其气候目标。</p><p>自《降低通货膨胀法案》通过以来，我们已开始为企业大规模投资提供长期确定性。随着需求方和供应方税收优惠政策的扩大，清洁能源行业的公司正在寻找更大的商业理由来投资美国，从而为美国创造高质量、高薪的就业机会。 《降低通货膨胀法案》正在帮助推动美国工厂建设支出的繁荣，自 2021 年底以来，该支出实际增长了一倍。自拜登总统上任以来，企业已承诺在清洁能源和制造业方面投资超过 5000 亿美元。</p><p>我看到全国各地出现了这些绿芽。本周在拉斯维加斯，我与一个电力工人工会的成员进行了交谈，该工会称《减少通货膨胀法案》是“历史性的胜利”。该法律要求公司支付现行工资并遵守学徒要求，以获得其许多激励措施的全部价值。该法律促进对低收入社区和历史上依赖化石燃料就业和收入的社区的投资。作为该法律早期影响的一个例子，评论员现在将中西部和南部称为新的“电池带”，因为那里电动汽车电池工厂的兴起。</p><p>扩大经济机会不仅在道德上是正确的，而且也是良好的经济学。研究表明，对服务不足的社区进行投资可以带来更大的经济效益。这意味着纳税人的资源得到了更有效的利用，整体经济的效益也得到了放大。</p><p> 《降低通货膨胀法案》也增强了我们的经济弹性。尽管石油价格在过去一年大幅下跌，但俄罗斯残酷入侵乌克兰后油价飙升给许多家庭带来了巨大困难。建设清洁能源经济意味着减少美国对化石燃料的依赖以及控制化石燃料的独裁政权的影响，为家庭和企业的能源成本提供更大的确定性。 《降低通货膨胀法案》旨在通过节省电动汽车、热泵和其他节能设备的成本，让家庭更容易实现这一转变。</p><p>但我们的战略比这更加雄心勃勃。推进美国能源安全还意味着减少关键清洁能源供应链过度集中的风险，这种风险会造成潜在的瓶颈并增加中断的可能性。 《降低通货膨胀法案》的双管齐下首先是建立我们的工业基础，同时鼓励企业与值得信赖的贸易伙伴合作，建立清洁能源投入和产品的安全全球供应链。去年，我们开始建立正式机制来促进这些努力。</p><p> 《降低通货膨胀法案》是国家保护地球和塑造繁荣、包容和有弹性的经济未来努力的转折点。</p><p><em>耶伦女士是财政部长。</em> </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=030EE4E1-084C-4369-AE30-4167FC65B664&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fa-prosperous-year-for-the-inflation-reduction-act-climate-change-net-zero-heat-global-warming-c2c07f0f&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">期刊社论报告：进步政策促成了橙色烟雾风暴。图片：美联社/NurPhoto 来自 ZUMA Press 综合：Mark Kelly<span class="imageCredit">华尔街日报互动版</span></p></div></div></section></div></main></div>]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 15 Aug 2023 22:07:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/a-prosperous-year-for-the-inflation-reduction-act-climate-change-net-zero-heat-global-warming-c2c07f0f</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/a-prosperous-year-for-the-inflation-reduction-act-climate-change-net-zero-heat-global-warming-c2c07f0f<category>气候变化</category><category>气候</category><category>全球暖化</category><category>热</category><category>伊拉</category><category>减少通货膨胀法案</category><category>投资</category><category>净零</category><category>清洁能源</category><category>机动车</category><category>替代燃料汽车</category><category>汽车</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>气候变化</category><category>自然环境</category><category>全球/世界问题</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论/意见</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>观点</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>自然环境</category><category>全球的</category><category>世界问题</category><category>政治</category><category>国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论</category><category>意见</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>观点</category><category>机动车</category><category>替代燃料汽车</category><category>汽车</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[A Sanitized ‘French Connection’ vs. the Hip-Hop Gutter]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>审查机构对一部已有 50 年历史的电影进行了审查，以消除孩子们每天在流行音乐中听到的种族歧视内容。 <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB12382406795447313640804590151283362695158"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB12382406795447313640804590151283362695158"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="columnist_mini"> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/jason-l-riley"><img width="45" height="45" src="https://s.wsj.net/public/resources/images/B3-BS054_riley__AM_20180912120933.jpg" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></a></div><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/jason-l-riley" itemprop="url" rel="author">杰森·莱利</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 15 日下午 6:05 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/a-sanitized-french-connection-vs-the-hip-hop-gutter-film-music-rap-slur-culture-the-exorcist-6b8f73d0"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-836108?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> 8 月 11 日，说唱歌手 Ice Cube 在纽约布朗克斯。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：爱德华多·穆诺兹/路透社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>30年前大学毕业搬到纽约的一大亮点是二轮电影院，它们让我有机会看到经典电影——《阿拉伯的劳伦斯》、《王牌进洞》、《后窗》、《甜蜜蜜》成功的味道”——在大屏幕上，正如它们的预期那样。</p><p>一些放映场挤满了电影爱好者，而另一些放映场却奇怪地空无一人，因为这座城市人口超过七百万。 20 世纪 90 年代末的一个晚上，我在 42 街的一家影院看了《驱魔人》。也许还有十几个人出现。唯一比几乎空无一人的剧院更令人惊讶的是我非常不喜欢这部电影，尤其是考虑到它被誉为有史以来最伟大的恐怖电影之一。对于一部 1973 年上映的电影来说，表演看起来不错，特效也令人印象深刻。不过，我觉得这个关于一个 12 岁女孩被魔鬼附身的故事与其说是恐怖，不如说是令人厌恶。</p><p> The movie&#39;s most famous scenes are when the girl, Regan, vomits into the face of a priest and when she slowly rotates her head until it&#39;s facing backward. Elsewhere in the film, however, she urinates on a carpet in front of guests at a dinner party, defaces a statue of the Virgin Mary, and stabs herself repeatedly in the crotch with a crucifix and then rubs her mother&#39;s face in the blood. “The Exorcist” doesn&#39;t wear its misogyny lightly. For most of the film, you&#39;re watching grown men torment a helpless little girl with escalating cruelty.</p><p> “It&#39;s easy to see why people, especially women, detested the picture,” Peter Biskind wrote in “Easy Riders, Raging Bulls,” his acclaimed history of the era&#39;s defining movies. “It presents a male nightmare of female puberty. Emergent female sexuality is equated with demonic possession, and the men in the picture—almost all celibate priests—unite to abuse and torture Regan.”</p><p> William Friedkin, who directed the film, died last week at 87. Two years before “The Exorcist,” he made another pathbreaking movie, “The French Connection,” which collected Oscars for best picture and best director. “The French Connection” stars Gene Hackman as Jimmy “Popeye” Doyle, a New York City detective who&#39;s trying to bust up an international drug-smuggling ring. There “were no clear-cut heroes and villains” in the film, Mr. Biskind wrote. “Friedkin resisted Hackman&#39;s inclination to sentimentalize his character.” So much for that.</p><p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/NYT" class="company-name">The New York Times</a> recently reported that a version of the “The French Connection” now available for streaming edits out a scene early in the film in which Doyle uses a racial slur to refer to a black suspect who stabbed Doyle&#39;s partner while resisting arrest. Apparently, lurid and sensationalistic depictions of a preteen girl performing lewd acts with a religious object are fine, but realistic cop dialogue in a 50-year-old movie somehow offends current sensibilities. The censors are worried about the N-word, but it&#39;s difficult to take that concern seriously. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4> Read More Upward Mobility</h4><p></p><ul class="articleList"><li> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/australia-asks-voters-to-expand-a-racial-welfare-state-social-justice-indigenous-aboriginal-223c820b?mod=article_relatedinline" target="_self" class="icon none">Australia Asks Voters to Expand a Racial Welfare State</a> <span class="date">August 8, 2023</span></li><li> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/jesse-jackson-turned-the-civil-rights-cause-into-an-industry-push-coalition-mlk-9d72eb7a?mod=article_relatedinline" target="_self" class="icon none">Jesse Jackson Turned the Civil-Rights Cause Into an Industry</a> <span class="date">July 18, 2023</span></li><li> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/liberals-cant-comprehend-black-economic-progress-real-estate-interest-rates-893b647?mod=article_relatedinline" target="_self" class="icon none">Liberals Can&#39;t Comprehend Black Economic Progress</a> <span class="date">July 11, 2023</span></li></ul></div></div><p> Earlier this month, fans of hip-hop marked the 50th anniversary of the musical genre&#39;s creation. It would be difficult to name another cultural phenomenon that has done more than hip-hop to normalize—if not popularize—use of a racial slur. Children today are far more likely to hear the word coming from a black person than a white person. Americans of all racial and ethnic backgrounds now dance, sing and laugh—seen a Dave Chappelle stand-up routine lately?—to entertainers who spew the term with abandon.</p><p> A-list hip-hop artists such as Jay-Z, Dr. Dre and Puff Daddy became fabulously wealthy trafficking in racist gutter lyrics and ugly stereotypes about black people. For decades, black parents have devoted an inordinate amount of time—with mixed success—to shielding their children from the materialism, drugs, promiscuous sex and thuggish behavior that pervade the songs of some of hip-hop&#39;s most popular artists. They aren&#39;t worried about their kids watching “The French Connection.”</p><p> Chuck D of Public Enemy, a pioneering rap group, took pride in spreading degeneracy among the younger generation. “You walk into a fourth or fifth grade black school today,” he told the Village Voice in 1991. “I&#39;m telling you, you&#39;re finding chaos right now, &#39;cause rappers came in the game and threw that confusing element in it, and kids is like, Yo, f— this.”</p><p> For generations, pop music has been a vehicle for adolescent rebellion, but we&#39;re a long way from worrying about Elvis&#39;s gyrating hips or the Beatles singing about their acid trips. Decades of glorifying the gangsta-rap lifestyle and, worse, presenting it as the only authentic black experience, have come at a cost. This is the hip-hop legacy that must be confronted sooner or later by people eager to edit an ugly word out of an old movie while ignoring its continuing use—and the implications of its use—in so many other contexts. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=A385DE1C-F70D-402A-98B9-3B5374C21F0F&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fa-sanitized-french-connection-vs-the-hip-hop-gutter-film-music-rap-slur-culture-the-exorcist-6b8f73d0&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">期刊编辑报告：金·斯特拉塞尔 (Kim Strassel)、凯特·巴舍尔德·奥德尔 (Kate Bachelder Odell)、阿莉西亚·芬利 (Alysia Finley) 和丹·亨宁格 (Dan Henninger) 分享了本周最好和最差的内容。图片来源：Scott Morgan/Reuters<span class="imageCredit">华尔街日报互动版</span></p></div></div></section></div></main></div>]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 15 Aug 2023 22:05:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/a-sanitized-french-connection-vs-the-hip-hop-gutter-film-music-rap-slur-culture-the-exorcist-6b8f73d0</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/a-sanitized-french-connection-vs-the-hip-hop-gutter-film-music-rap-slur-culture-the-exorcist-6b8f73d0<author><![CDATA[Jason L. Riley]]></author><category>纽约</category><category>rap</category><category> hip hop</category><category>音乐</category><category>电影</category><category>恐怖</category><category>文化</category><category>censor</category><category> slur</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>社会/社区</category><category>歧视</category><category>艺术/娱乐</category><category>人权/公民自由</category><category>电影</category><category>种族主义/仇外心理</category><category>社会问题</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论/意见</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>社会</category><category>社区</category><category>歧视</category><category>艺术</category><category>娱乐</category><category>人权</category><category>公民权利</category><category>电影</category><category>种族主义</category><category>仇外心理</category><category>社会问题</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论</category><category>意见</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Why Are Carbon Emissions Up?]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Green subsidies aren&#39;t working when CO2 is growing faster than energy consumption. <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB12382406795447313640804590152240588628962"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB12382406795447313640804590152240588628962"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="columnist_mini"> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/holman-w-jenkinsjr"><img width="45" height="45" src="https://s.wsj.net/public/resources/images/B3-BI571_jenkin_AM_20180807123815.jpg" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></a></div><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name">Holman W. Jenkins</span> , <span class="author" itemprop="name">Jr.</span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> Aug. 15, 2023 6:04 pm ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/carbon-emissions-up-inflation-reduction-act-biden-climate-change-renewable-green-energy-subsidy-b5d90085"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-836114?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> A car has its emissions measured.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Frank Hoermann / Sven Simon/Zuma Press</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Hooray, the climate problem is solved. At least if the new spending estimates under Joe Biden&#39;s Inflation Reduction Act are matched by similar expected declines in emissions.</p><p> The <a href="https://finance.yahoo.com/news/bidens-green-energy-law-is-turning-out-to-be-huge-201035230.html" target="_blank" class="icon none">estimated</a> spending has tripled, to $1.2 trillion, so the estimated benefits must have tripled too. Instead of a 40% drop, US emissions will be down 120%. We&#39;ll be sucking CO2 out of the air.</p><p> I&#39;m joking, of course, but so were the original estimates by three private groups touted last year by the White House. All three ignored the price effect: When certain consumers are subsidized to use less fossil energy, others in the US and world will take advantage of lower prices to consume more.</p><p> One outfit, the Rhodium Group, lamely said it was putting off consideration of such “energy system outcomes” for a future “deeper dive.” Another, EnergyInnovation.org, lost itself in the weeds of Mr. Biden&#39;s domestic oil and gas leasing policies.</p><p> Least dishonest was the Princeton University-connected REPEAT Project. It omitted the effect of lower fuel prices on emissions but included them as a side benefit for fossil-fuel consumers. (If the person reading over your shoulder is cackling, she&#39;s an economist.)</p><p> Even the White House Office of Management and Budget couldn&#39;t conceal a guilty conscience. In trumpeting the private studies, it noted that “complicated economic interactions” might affect “real-world” emissions.</p><p> How are Americans supposed to evaluate the policies of their government if even supposedly independent private analysts enlist in the cause of propaganda? Good question.</p><p> Meanwhile, a censorious report on National Public Radio, citing a poll, accuses Republican voters of being content to “do nothing” about climate change. In fact, neither party proposes to do anything about climate change. Democrats propose to spend a lot more money doing nothing.</p><p> It helps to be realistic about our energy economy, including the term “alternative” energy. As much wood is burned in the US today as in 1885, when coal surpassed it to become our largest energy source. Wind and hydropower were in use centuries before fossil fuels arrived and never stopped growing. Solar voltaic has grown like topsy since its invention in the 1950s.</p><p> There&#39;s only “additional” energy and no upward limit on humanity&#39;s willingness to consume it except through the workings of price. If energy were cheap enough, we&#39;d have flying cars, supersonic airlines and space travel for the middle class. You would open your windows in the winter to enjoy the benefit of fresh air and heat at the same time. Energy is convenience. Energy is control over our environment. Humans will consume all the energy it makes sense to consume at the available price.</p><p> When President Obama launched today&#39;s worldwide gush of green-energy subsidies in 2009, his allies in Congress added financing for a National Academy of Sciences study, which would later conclude, at a length of 198 pages, that such subsidies were a “poor tool for reducing greenhouse gases and achieving climate-change objectives.” </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4> Read More Business World</h4><p></p><ul class="articleList"><li> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/special-counsel-2024-election-trump-hunter-biden-david-weiss-merrick-garland-archer-burisma-smith-877d416?mod=article_relatedinline" target="_self" class="icon none">&#39;Special Counsel&#39; Becomes a 2024 Election Joke</a> <span class="date">August 11, 2023</span></li><li> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/impeaching-a-trump-impeachment-hunter-biden-partisan-investigation-ukraine-gop-election-847d972?mod=article_relatedinline" target="_self" class="icon none">Impeaching a Trump Impeachment</a> <span class="date">August 8, 2023</span></li><li> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/its-doj-vs-doj-in-the-2024-race-hunter-joe-biden-trump-indictment-smith-429971ee?mod=article_relatedinline" target="_self" class="icon none">It&#39;s DOJ vs. DOJ in the 2024 Election</a> <span class="date">August 4, 2023</span></li></ul></div></div><p> The numbers bear this out. Worldwide investment in renewable energy, by some dubious measures, has exceeded investment in fossil fuels in recent years, yet this merely testifies to how inefficient such investments are in producing energy output. Cut to the chase: global CO2 emissions actually grew <a href="https://www.enerdata.net/publications/reports-presentations/world-energy-trends.html" target="_blank" class="icon none">12% faster</a> in 2022 than energy consumption did.</p><p> With deployments goosed by Obama-like handouts around the world, wind and solar still accounted for less than 2.4% of humanity&#39;s total energy consumption. Their annual increase was still a small fraction of the annual increase in fossil-fuel consumption. They remain functionally additive to humanity&#39;s energy budget, rather than displacing coal or oil on a global basis.</p><p> I&#39;ve referred in the past to the problem of “sophisticated state failure.” Miracles can&#39;t be expected, but there&#39;s no reason democratic societies can&#39;t improve their ability to address complex problems. Needed is a news media able to think and communicate in multi-variable terms rather than single-variable terms (eg, green energy = good).</p><p> In the absence of a carbon tax, green-energy subsidies mainly stimulate more energy consumption overall. In the presence of a carbon tax, they&#39;re redundant and make carbon-saving decisions less efficient than they would otherwise be.</p><p> This isn&#39;t hard but it&#39;s too hard for today&#39;s media, and the output is Team Biden&#39;s Inflation Reduction Act.</p><p> At least one honest climate advocate works in the administration—whoever was responsible for its recent endorsement of research into geoengineering, or injecting particles into the atmosphere to slow warming even as our green subsidies uselessly accumulate in the pockets of green-energy lobbyists <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB122869112877186439?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">like</a> Al Gore. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=5C9F03FE-C876-4D1E-AE10-118553A4B17B&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fcarbon-emissions-up-inflation-reduction-act-biden-climate-change-renewable-green-energy-subsidy-b5d90085&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption"> Journal Editorial Report: Its tailpipe emission standards turn auto companies into public utilities.图片：美联社/法新社/盖蒂图片社 综合：马克·凯利<span class="imageCredit">华尔街日报互动版</span></p></div></div></section></div></main></div>]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 15 Aug 2023 22:04:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/carbon-emissions-up-inflation-reduction-act-biden-climate-change-renewable-green-energy-subsidy-b5d90085</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/carbon-emissions-up-inflation-reduction-act-biden-climate-change-renewable-green-energy-subsidy-b5d90085<category> barack obama</category><category> climate change</category><category> global warming</category><category> environment</category><category> green energy</category><category> renewable energy</category><category>碳</category><category>化石燃料</category><category>fracking</category><category>太阳的</category><category>al gore</category><category> ira</category><category> inflation reduction act</category><category>法规/政府政策</category><category>政府援助/赠款</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>Air Pollution</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>Climate Change</category><category>自然环境</category><category>Global/World Issues</category><category> Environmental Pollution</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论/意见</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>规定</category><category>政府政策</category><category>政府援助</category><category>赠款</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>air pollution</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>自然环境</category><category>global</category><category> world issues</category><category> environmental pollution</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论</category><category>意见</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[‘Winner Sells All’ Review: Battle of Bricks and Clicks]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Walmart executives were initially skeptical of online retail&#39;s future. Amazon&#39;s rise forced them to adapt. <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB11442211204531153375304590150390637189732"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-835457?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> An Amazon Prime delivery van sits parked near a Walmart store in Richmond, Calif.</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：贾斯汀·沙利文/盖蒂图片社</p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB11442211204531153375304590150390637189732"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name">Marc Levinson</span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> Aug. 15, 2023 6:02 pm ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/winner-sells-all-review-battle-of-bricks-and-clicks-c40d56b5"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> In 1995, a startup called <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/AMZN" class="">Amazon</a> <span class="company-name-type">.</span> com began selling books on the World Wide Web from the garage of a house near Seattle. A few months later, <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/WMT" class="">Walmart</a> <span class="company-name-type">,</span> the world&#39;s biggest retailer, tiptoed into the future by offering holiday gift baskets on the web. Neither venture enjoyed instant success. Amazon, wildly burning cash to build its business, would not book substantial earnings for another two decades. Walmart would churn through strategy after strategy as it struggled to mesh online retailing with its very profitable base of almost 5,000 US stores.</p><p> Jason Del Rey&#39;s “Winner Sells All: Amazon, Walmart, and the Battle for Our Wallets” offers an engrossing account of the clash between these two giants. This is no bird&#39;s-eye view: The author knows both companies well, and he is not afraid of plumbing the details of their attempts to meet their customers online. While retailing is his nominal topic, Mr. Del Rey&#39;s real subject is the difficulty of driving change in a large organization. His book will fascinate anybody who is trying to run one. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/schemas/38bc97a8-6189-43a0-a8a9-5a9db88e6c7f.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p> In its earliest days, Amazon seemed more of a nuisance than a challenger to executives at Walmart&#39;s Bentonville, Ark., headquarters. Although Amazon poached key Walmart technologists as early as 1997, Walmart&#39;s annual revenue that year was nearly 700 times Amazon&#39;s and growing at a double-digit rate. David Glass, then Walmart&#39;s chief executive, rejected proposals to invest heavily in selling online. Walmart.com, Glass predicted, would never become a meaningful part of the company&#39;s business.</p><p> Walmart&#39;s lack of interest was partly cultural: Its executives were trained to cut costs, not to take gambles, and many of its customers lived in rural areas where high-speed internet service was years in the future. The high-tech precincts of Silicon Valley and Seattle were a foreign country. When executives from down-to-earth Bentonville visited Walmart&#39;s flashy e-commerce headquarters on San Francisco Bay, one interviewee told Mr. Del Rey, it was “like they were walking into a porn shop.”</p><p> But there were also good business reasons for Walmart to move slowly. “Online sales could siphon sales from the cash machine that was its Supercenter stores,” Mr. Del Rey observes. Store managers and division executives feared their performance and compensation would take a hit from online sales. If the quickest way to deliver an item ordered online was to pluck it from the shelves of a brick-and-mortar store near the customer&#39;s home, would the stores division or the online division receive the credit? If a store employee was assigned to gather an online grocery order for customer pickup, which division would bear the labor cost?</p><p> Within the corporate bureaucracy, such issues took years to resolve. As late as 2020, Walmart asked customers placing orders via smartphone to use an orange-colored app to buy groceries and a blue one for general merchandise. If the customer mistakenly typed “Legos” into the grocery app, Mr. Del Rey reports, the software would respond that the product was not available rather than filling the order.</p><p> Not that things were going seamlessly for Amazon. At one point, it offered customers the choice of three different virtual shopping carts, sometimes displaying different prices for similar items. It committed to matching Walmart&#39;s famously low prices, even tracking prices on competitors&#39; websites, but its price-matching never quite worked. An app that allowed a shopper to scan a product bar code in any store and immediately compare Amazon&#39;s price incited a nationwide uproar amid claims that Amazon was spying on mom-and-pop shops. With Walmart&#39;s prices typically lower in stores than on Walmart.com and varying by location, Amazon couldn&#39;t figure out which price to meet—and how to adjust for its delivery costs. Eventually, Amazon abandoned its claim to match all prices and had its website declare an item out of stock when Walmart&#39;s price was too low to match profitably.</p><p> Walmart hoped its 2016 acquisition of Jet.com, a year-old online retailer, would revive its lagging online operation. Walmart paid $3.3 billion and put Jet&#39;s founder, Marc Lore, in charge of Walmart.com. Within a year, Walmart swallowed internet-oriented fashion retailers Bonobos and ModCloth, footwear website ShoeBuy, and outdoor-gear store Moosejaw; opened an outlet called Store No. 8 to test new ideas; and beat Amazon to offer to-the-fridge grocery delivery. Its share price soared, along with its online sales. “The pace of action and change was astounding for a company like Walmart,” Mr. Del Rey writes. Perhaps too much so. After Walmart.com repeatedly failed to meet its financial targets, Mr. Lore departed, and most of the acquisitions were sold off. Only in 2020 did Walmart belatedly merge its online and in-store sales efforts into a single business.</p><p> Both companies have struggled to profitably expand into new product lines, such as healthcare and video. And both have spotty records abroad: Amazon.com was pushed out of China and managed to gain a retail foothold in South Korea only through a deal with a local online retailer, while Walmart has exited Japan, Germany, Brazil and South Korea. “Winner Sells All” makes no mention of <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/BABA" class="">Alibaba</a> <span class="company-name-type">,</span> the Chinese merchandising and cloud-computing giant, and <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/CPNG" class="">Coupang</a> <span class="company-name-type">,</span></p> which is dominant in South Korea, but these and other foreign-based companies may have the scale and know-how to threaten both Amazon&#39;s and Walmart&#39;s positions in online retailing.<p></p><p> Mr. Del Rey thinks that Amazon&#39;s aggressive instincts and quick execution are winning the battle with Walmart. But while Amazon has more online customers—168 million US households pay annual fees to Amazon Prime—its profits come mainly from cloud-computing services, and its North American retail business consistently underperforms Walmart&#39;s (measured by operating income as a percentage of sales). Amazon&#39;s attempts to compensate for Walmart&#39;s enormous fleet of physical stores by building high-tech stores of its own have flopped. Despite massive investments, including the 2017 acquisition of Whole Foods Market, Amazon poses little threat to Walmart&#39;s leadership of the US grocery market. The intense contest that Mr. Del Rey so vividly portrays is by no means over.</p><p> <em>Mr. Levinson&#39;s books include “The Great A&amp;P and the Struggle for Small Business in America.”</em></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 15 Aug 2023 22:02:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/winner-sells-all-review-battle-of-bricks-and-clicks-c40d56b5</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/winner-sells-all-review-battle-of-bricks-and-clicks-c40d56b5<category> Retail/Wholesale</category><category> Mixed Retailing</category><category> Etailing</category><category> Shopping Malls/Superstores</category><category>电子商务</category><category>在线服务提供商</category><category>零售</category><category>技术</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>图书</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>艺术/娱乐</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 排除过滤器</category><category>评论</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>观点</category><category>亚马逊</category><category>AMZN</category><category>沃尔玛</category><category>WMT</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>图书</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>艺术</category><category>娱乐</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>c&amp;e 排除过滤器</category><category>评论</category><category>观点</category><category>retail</category><category>批发的</category><category>mixed retailing</category><category> etailing</category><category> shopping malls</category><category> superstores</category><category>电子商务</category><category>在线服务提供商</category><category>技术</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Notable & Quotable: The Pelosi Building]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> &#39;Dozens of dealers routinely plant themselves on, next to or across the street from the property, operating in shifts as users smoke, snort or shoot up their recent purchases.&#39; <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB11442211204531153375304590152522527871164"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB11442211204531153375304590152522527871164"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> Aug. 15, 2023 6:02 pm ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/notable-quotable-the-pelosi-building-homeless-housing-drugs-remote-work-69edee08"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-836096?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Homeless people outside of the Federal Building in San Francisco, June 6.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Tayfun Coskun/Anadolu Agency via Getty Images</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> <em>Megan Cassidy <a href="https://www.sfchronicle.com/sf/article/drugs-crime-nancy-pelosi-federal-building-18292237.php" target="_blank" class="icon none">reporting</a> for the San Francisco Chronicle, Aug. 11:</em></p><p> Officials at the US Department of Health and Human Services advised hundreds of employees in San Francisco to work remotely for the foreseeable future due to public safety concerns outside the <a href="https://www.wsj.com/topics/person/nancy-pelosi">Nancy Pelosi</a> Federal Building on Seventh Street. 。 。 。</p><p> The memo came on the same day that, according to Axios, President Biden&#39;s White House chief of staff called for more federal employees to return to their offices after years of remote work due to the COVID-19 pandemic. 。 。 。</p><p> The building has long been a locus of some of the city&#39;s most intractable problems.</p><p> Dozens of dealers routinely plant themselves on, next to or across the street from the property, operating in shifts as users smoke, snort or shoot up their recent purchases. The property&#39;s concrete benches are an especially popular site for users to get high, socialize or pass out.</p><p> While Pelosi&#39;s five-person staff was not advised to work remotely, she raised concerns about the building&#39;s tenant safety last week in a meeting with the US attorney for the northern district of California, according to officials with her office.</p><p> “The safety of workers in our federal buildings has always been a priority for Speaker Emerita Pelosi, whether in the building or on their commutes,” Pelosi spokesperson Aaron Bennett said in a statement.</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 15 Aug 2023 22:02:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/notable-quotable-the-pelosi-building-homeless-housing-drugs-remote-work-69edee08</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/notable-quotable-the-pelosi-building-homeless-housing-drugs-remote-work-69edee08<category> housing</category><category>无家可归</category><category>药物</category><category>remote</category><category> megan cassidy</category><category>备忘录</category><category>容量/设施</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>Work-Life Balance</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>General Labor Issues</category><category>生活/生活方式</category><category>Telecommuting</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论/意见</category><category>社论</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 排除过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>日常新闻</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category> Nancy Pelosi</category><category>容量</category><category>设施</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>work-life balance</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>general labor issues</category><category>活的</category><category>生活方式</category><category>telecommuting</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论</category><category>意见</category><category>社论</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>c&amp;e 排除过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>常规新闻</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Does Biden Regret Expressing Regret?]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> The White House celebrates the anniversary of the deceptively titled Inflation Reduction Act. <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB12263517457060764701004590152324129103904"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB12263517457060764701004590152324129103904"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="columnist_mini"> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/james-freeman"><img width="45" height="45" src="https://s.wsj.net/public/resources/images/B3-BG857_freema_AM_20180731103058.jpg" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></a></div><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/james-freeman" itemprop="url" rel="author">James Freeman</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> Aug. 15, 2023 5:58 pm ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/does-biden-regret-expressing-regret-15923477"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-836254?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> President Joe Biden speaks in Milwaukee on Tuesday.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Mark Hertzberg/Zuma Press</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> We live in an age marked by sharp differences of opinion between highly credentialed elites and average working stiffs. But both academic experts and rank-and-file voters seem to have reached a consensus that <a href="https://www.wsj.com/topics/person/joe-biden">Joe Biden</a> &#39;s economic program has not restrained consumer prices. This consensus may also include Mr. Biden.</p><p> Josh Boak and Paul Wiseman <a href="https://apnews.com/article/biden-inflation-reduction-climate-anniversary-9950f7e814ac71e89eee3f452ab17f71" target="_blank" class="icon none">report</a> for the Associated Press:</p><blockquote> Even President Joe Biden has some regrets about the name of the Inflation Reduction Act: As the giant law turns 1 on Wednesday, it&#39;s increasingly clear that immediately curbing prices wasn&#39;t the point.</blockquote><blockquote> While price increases have cooled over the past year — the inflation rate has dropped from 9% to 3.2% — most economists say little to none of the drop came from the law.</blockquote><blockquote> “I can&#39;t think of any mechanism by which it would have brought down inflation to date,” said Harvard University economist Jason Furman, who added that the law could eventually help to lower electricity bills.</blockquote><blockquote> Alex Arnon, an economic and budget analyst for the University of Pennsylvania&#39;s Penn Wharton Budget Model, offers a similar assessment.</blockquote><blockquote> “We can say with pretty strong confidence that it was mostly other factors that have brought inflation down,&#39;&#39; he said. “The IRA has just not been a significant factor.&#39;&#39;</blockquote><p> When the law passed a year ago, the Penn Wharton Budget Model and the Congressional Budget Office were among the many credentialed outfits forecasting that the massive tax-and-spending bill would not provide any meaningful inflation relief. But amid surging inflation Democrats figured that “Inflation Reduction Act” sounded good.</p><p> As for Mr. Biden&#39;s regrets, unfortunately it&#39;s not clear that he understands his mistakes. He discussed the subject last week in a rambling and incoherent speech at a Utah fund raiser. He seems to have admitted that the law was not about inflation reduction right before suggesting that it actually was.</p><p> Here&#39;s the section of the White House <a href="https://www.whitehouse.gov/briefing-room/speeches-remarks/2023/08/10/remarks-by-president-biden-at-a-campaign-reception-salt-lake-city-ut/" target="_blank" class="icon none">transcript</a> in which he addressed the Inflation Reduction Act:</p><blockquote> I wish I hadn&#39;t called it that, because it has less to do with reducing inflation than it does to do with dealing with providing for alternatives that generate economic growth. And so, we&#39;re now in a situation where if you take a look at what we&#39;re doing in the Inflation Reduction Act, we&#39;re literally reducing the cost of people being able to make their — meet their basic needs.</blockquote><p> Any of the well-heeled attendees at the fundraiser who were hoping for a clarification were unfortunately disappointed. Here&#39;s what Mr. Biden said next, according to the official transcript:</p><blockquote> And, for example, we&#39;re in a situation where we&#39;re — and the — about the Medicare prices, but — well, I&#39;m — I&#39;m going to go on too long for you.</blockquote><blockquote> But, look, some of my friends on the other team — and I met someone today who said, “I&#39;m a Republican. I&#39;m voting for you. I have a program; I used to be on (inaudible).” And now he said, “I&#39;m — I&#39;m voting for you.” I w- — I didn&#39;t ask why. (Laughter.)</blockquote><blockquote> Any rate, during this process, I&#39;ve been able to expand the amount — I made a commitment that one third of all the land and waters of America will be in conservation by the time I left office — one third. It&#39;s about 18 percent now. (Applause.)</blockquote><blockquote> But what&#39;s going on is that in the process of doing this, I&#39;m told of all this incredible amount of money we spend. But guess what? I reduced the debt $1 trillion 700 billion — (applause) — more than any president has ever — ever, ever — in American history.</blockquote><p> So much to applaud, right? Mr. Biden&#39;s titanic falsehood about debt reduction is one for the record books. <a href="https://fiscaldata.treasury.gov/datasets/debt-to-the-penny/debt-to-the-penny" target="_blank" class="icon none">According to the Biden Treasury Department</a> , total public debt outstanding has <em>increased</em> by nearly $5 trillion since the day Joe Biden took office. In contrast to his bogus claim of reducing debt, It&#39;s more accurate to say that Mr. Biden is the most fiscally reckless president in the history of the United States.</p><p> Could the applause have been sarcastic? One would have thought that even those who didn&#39;t immediately comprehend the scale of the Biden deception would have wondered why, if he was actually reducing debt, he had to spend much of this year demanding a debt limit <em>increase</em> from Congress.</p><p> Perhaps confused reception guests were too busy puzzling over his conflicting statements on inflation or his earlier claim that his 2021 American Rescue Plan “got the economy moving again,” which is contradicted by the GDP statistics published by his own Commerce Department. They show fast growth during the quarter he signed the measure, and much slower growth since.</p><p> In any case, while the president seems confused about whether his policies have been directed to inflation reduction, both academics and blue-collar workers seem to agree that they haven&#39;t.</p><p> This is why Democrats like Ruy Teixera are worried about 2024. They see their party embracing unpopular social policies in part because of a misplaced confidence that Mr. Biden will receive credit from voters for the economy.</p><p> Mr. Teixera <a href="https://www.liberalpatriot.com/p/brahmin-left-vs-populist-right" target="_blank" class="icon none">writes at his</a> Liberal Patriot Substack column:</p><blockquote> The fact is that the cultural left in and around the Democratic Party has managed to associate the party with a series of views on crime, immigration, policing, free speech, and of course race and gender that are quite far from those of the median working class voter (including the median nonwhite working-class voter)...</blockquote><blockquote> They do believe, however, that they have an ace in the hole that can overcome these liabilities with working class voters: “Bidenomics.” The idea is that the improving economic outlook, especially lowered inflation, plus the jobs generated by the Democrats&#39; various spending bills, will endear these voters to the Democrats and allow them to overlook the other things they don&#39;t like about the party and the Biden administration.</blockquote><blockquote> So far, this approach has decidedly not worked. As many outlets have reported, voters remain deeply unhappy about the economy and unconvinced by the Bidenomics pitch. In the most recent CNN poll, working-class voters give Biden just a 32 percent approval rating on the economy and a 24 percent rating on handling inflation; about four-fifths characterize the current economy as poor. And in the most recent CBS poll, most hadn&#39;t heard much about Bidenomics and of those who had the term was mostly associated with higher inflation.</blockquote><p> Who&#39;s applauding now?</p><p> ***</p><p> <em>James Freeman is the co-author of <a href="https://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/1982163984" target="_blank" class="icon none">“The Cost: Trump, China and American Revival”</a> and also the co-author of <a href="https://www.amazon.com/Borrowed-Time-Centuries-Booms-Bailouts/dp/0062669877/ref=asc_df_0062669877/?tag=hyprod-20&amp;linkCode=df0&amp;hvadid=312143020546&amp;hvpos=&amp;hvnetw=g&amp;hvrand=10412016619786864649&amp;hvpone=&amp;hvptwo=&amp;hvqmt=&amp;hvdev=c&amp;hvdvcmdl=&amp;hvlocint=&amp;hvlocphy=9003741&amp;hvtargid=pla-525185269824&amp;psc=1" target="_blank" class="icon none">“Borrowed Time: Two Centuries of Booms, Busts and Bailouts at Citi.”</a></em></p><p> ***</p><p> Follow James Freeman on <a href="https://twitter.com/FreemanWSJ" target="_blank" class="icon none">Twitter</a> .</p><p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/newsletters?sub=157&amp;mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">Subscribe to the Best of the Web email.</a></p><p> To suggest items, please email best@wsj.com.</p><p> (Teresa Vozzo helps compile Best of the Web.)</p><p> ***</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 15 Aug 2023 21:58:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/does-biden-regret-expressing-regret-15923477</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/does-biden-regret-expressing-regret-15923477<author><![CDATA[James Freeman]]></author><category>经济表现/指标</category><category>Inflation Figures/Price Indices</category><category>经济新闻</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论/意见</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>观点</category><category>Joe Biden</category><category>经济表现</category><category>指标</category><category>inflation figures</category><category> price indices</category><category>经济新闻</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论</category><category>意见</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category